<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06058074 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06058074 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  DISCRIMINATION; CIVIL; RIGHT; ...; RESTAURANT; COMPANY; POLICY; EMPLOYMENT;END; HOMOSEXUAL; CAUSE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A chain of country-style restaurants has backed down from a policy banningemployment of homosexuals, but gay activists say the damage has been done.;   Cracker Barrel Old Country Stores Inc. fired several employees this monthbased on a policy banning homosexual employees, said Robert Bray, spokesmanfor the National Gay and Lesbian Task Force, in Washington, D.C.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  General News  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  ANTI-GAY RESTAURANT POLICY RESCINDED  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The chain of about 100 eateries, based in Lebanon, Tenn., and locatedmainly along interstates in the Southeast and Midwest, issued the policyearlier this month, stating it wanted to uphold traditional American values.;   'Inconsistent' with customers;  It &quot;is perceived to be inconsistent withthose of our customer base to continue to employ individuals . . . whosesexual preferences fail to demonstrate normal heterosexual values which havebeen the foundation of families in our society,&quot; wrote William A. Bridges,vice president of human resources for Cracker Barrel.;    Bridges could not bereached for comment this morning.;    But Dan W. Evins, the company chairman,told the (Nashville) Tennessean newspaper Tuesday that &quot;a written policy gotout that should not have gotten out.&quot;;    &quot;We told the gay community that wasa mistake; we apologized, rescinded it.;    &quot;As of now we have no policyregarding gays and lesbians,&quot; Evins said.;    However, Evins said gay orlesbian applicants would not be employed if there was the potential fordisruption in some rural communities.;    Four firings confirmed;  Bray saidhe had confirmed with three men and one woman that they had been fired fromCracker Barrel stores in Norcross, Tifton and Douglasville, Ga. He said he hadheard of a couple of firings in Tennessee and North Carolina but could notconfirm them.;    Cracker Barrel officials wouldn't say how the employees wereidentified as being gay, Bray said.;    Bray said Bridges issued a statementFriday backing away from the anti-gay policy when Cracker Barrel was contactedby the task force and other gay organizations.;    But he said the statementis &quot;unacceptable to the gay community and further defames lesbians and gays.&quot;;   Abby Rubenfeld, co-chair of the Tennessee Gay andamp; Lesbian Alliance and amember of the task force board, said activists will meet in Nashville tonightto discuss action.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Nashville, Tenn.  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910227  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  February  </MONTH><PG.COL>  7F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  365  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday February 27, 199100058074,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>